-access_aggregation_dsl_inner_vlan

Supported platforms Details

IxNetwork

DESCRIPTION

The inner VLAN ID that will be used for all the subscriber packets in the ANCP range. This parameter is supported using the following APIs: IxTclNetwork.

DEFAULT

1

-access_aggregation_dsl_inner_vlan_type

Supported platforms Details

IxNetwork

DESCRIPTION

The type of aggregation for inner vlan. This parameter is supported using the following APIs: IxTclNetwork.

Valid options are:

actual_dsl_subscriber_vlan

The TLV will use the actual inner VLAN ID of the DSL subscriber (identified by PPPoE session, DHCP lease, or IP interface). If inner VLAN is disabled for the correspondent PPP/DHCP/IP structure, 0 will be set in the TLV.

custom

The inner VLAN ID that is specified by -access_aggregation_dsl_inner_vlan will be used for all the subscriber packets in the ANCP range.

DEFAULT

actual_dsl_subscriber_vlan

-circuit_id

Supported platforms Details

IxNetwork

DESCRIPTION

Defines one or more circuit IDs for the subscribers in the specific ANCP range. Circuit IDs enable the NAS to associate individual subscribers with distinct QoS requirements. Circuit ID is a string value, from 0 to 63 characters in length. The format strings can include normal alpha-numeric characters interspersed with instances of %-prefixed specifications. There are 5 %-prefixed specifications that can be used. This parameter is supported using the following APIs: IxTclNetwork.

Valid options are:

%L

Outer VLAN ID: Inserts the two-digit outer VLAN ID into the field. For example: "vlan%L" will generate vlan01 for clients on VLAN 1 and vlan02 for clients on VLAN 2. Use only with ethernet ports.

%I

Inner VLAN ID: Inserts the two-digit inner VLAN ID into the field. For example: "vlan%I" will generate vlan01 for clients on INNER VLAN 1 and vlan02 for clients on INNER VLAN 2. Use only with ethernet ports.

%v

VPI: Inserts the two-digit VPI into the field. For example: "vpi%v" will generate vpi01 for clients on VPI 1 and vpi02 for clients on VPI 2. Use only with atm ports.

%V

VCI: Inserts the two-digit VCI into the field. For example: "vci%V"will generate vci01 for clients on VCI 1 and vci02 for clients on VCI 2. Use only with atm ports.

%i

This is the most flexible of the commands, allowing an incrementing value to be specified. Three parameters control the operation of this option. <br/><br/> Start Value: The Start-width value is the first value to be used. Its width will be preserved when values are incremented. For example: `%001i' will generate 001, 002, 003, and so forth. <br/><br/> Count: The Count value specifies how many values will be generated before the first value is repeated. For example: `%001:3i' will generate 001, 002, 003, 001, 002, 003, 001, and so forth. That is, count values will be generated and then the start value will be repeated. <br/><br/> Repeat Count: The Repeat value specifies how many times each value will be repeated. For example: `%001::2i' will generate 001, 001, 002, 002, 003, 003, and so forth.

DEFAULT

circuit

-distribution_alg_percentage

Supported platforms Details

IxNetwork

DESCRIPTION

Defines the percentage of deviation from a uniform distribution of DSL subscribers-to-access nodes. With the default value of 0%, the DSL subscribers are distributed among the access nodes according to the following algorithm: If the division of the number of subscribers by the number of access nodes produces a remainder of zero, the DSL subscribers are equally distributed among the access nodes. For example, if you have four access nodes and 80 subscribers, the default value of 0% results in an equal allocation of 20 subscribers to each access node.

If the division of the number of subscribers by the number of access nodes produces a non-zero remainder, the DSL subscribers are equally distributed among the access nodes, with the remaining number of nodes distributed equally, beginning with the first access node. For example, with eight subscribers and three access nodes, the distribution will be as follows: access node 1 will receive subscribers 0, 1, and 2; access node 2 will receive subscribers 3, 4, and 5; and access node 3 will receive subscribers 6 and 7.

If you set Distribution Algorithm Percentage to a value greater than zero, the distribution is accomplished according to the following algorithm: 1. First, IxNetwork calculates an even distribution of subscribers, using the method described above. 2. Next, IxNetwork groups the access nodes into pairs. If there is an odd number of access nodes, the last access node will keep its currently-allocated subscribers. 3. For each pair of access nodes, IxNetwork uses the percent of deviation to calculate the number of subscribers to move from the first access node to the second access node. For example, if you have four access nodes, 80 subscribers, and a Distribution Algorithm Percentage value of 50%, IxNetwork will move 50% of the subscribers from the first access node in each pair to the second access node. In this example, the first access node in each pair will have 10 subscribers, and the second access node will have 30 subscribers. The default is 0%, the minimum is 0%, and the maximum is 100%. Note: The accuracy of the DSL profile distribution increases as the number of emulated DSL subscribers grows. If you have between 50 and 100 subscribers, you may experience an deviation of 10 to 15 percent from the model. This parameter is supported using the following APIs: IxTclNetwork.

DEFAULT

0

-encap_type

Supported platforms Details

IxNetwork

DESCRIPTION

Framing mode for encapsulated ANCP device. Ixia supports ETHERNETII, VccMuxIPV4Routed, VccMuxBridgedEthernetFCS, VccMuxBridgedEthernetNoFCS, VccMuxIPV6Routed, SNAP, LLCBridgedEthernetFCS, LLCBridgedEthernetNoFCS, LLCPPPoA, VccMuxPPPoA. -events_per_interval

Supported platforms Details

IxNetwork

DESCRIPTION

When only events_per_interval is present, this represents the number of Port Up and Port Down event messages to send each second. This is a port level setting. This parameter is supported using the following APIs: IxTclNetwork. If is necessary to configure separate Port Up and Port Down frequency please use global_port_up_rate and global_port_down_rate, or port_up_rate and port_down_rate and port_override_globals. Default behavior is port_override_globals 1, port_up_rate 50 and port_down_rate 50.

DEFAULT

 None

DESCRIPTION

The Maximum Segment Size. The MSS is the largest amount of data, specified in bytes, that the IP device can transmit as a single, unfragmented unit. The TCP MSS equals the MTU minus the TCP header size, minus the IP header size. Stack Manager supports jumbo frames. Therefore the maximum value is 9460. This option configures the MSS value for the Access Node.

-port_override_globals

IxNetwork

DESCRIPTION

If selected, all the rate settings defined at the global level will be overridden by the rate settings defined on this port. For example, if you have set the Port Up rate to 100 on the global level, and you have defined two ports, these 100 events will be evenly distributed across the ports (50 for each). If you then enable Override Global Rate, you can modify the number of events for each of the ports (such as changing the distribution from 50-50 to 60-40). circuit_id

Supported platforms Details

IxNetwork

DESCRIPTION

Defines one or more circuit IDs for the subscribers in the specific ANCP range. Circuit IDs enable the NAS to associate individual subscribers with distinct QoS requirements. Circuit ID is a string value, from 0 to 63 characters in length. The format strings can include normal alpha-numeric characters interspersed with instances of %-prefixed specifications. There are 5 %-prefixed specifications that can be used. This parameter is supported using the following APIs: IxTclNetwork.

Valid options are:

%L

Outer VLAN ID: Inserts the two-digit outer VLAN ID into the field. For example: "vlan%L" will generate vlan01 for clients on VLAN 1 and vlan02 for clients on VLAN 2. Use only with ethernet ports.

%I

Inner VLAN ID: Inserts the two-digit inner VLAN ID into the field. For example: "vlan%I" will generate vlan01 for clients on INNER VLAN 1 and vlan02 for clients on INNER VLAN 2. Use only with ethernet ports.

%v

VPI: Inserts the two-digit VPI into the field. For example: "vpi%v" will generate vpi01 for clients on VPI 1 and vpi02 for clients on VPI 2. Use only with atm ports.

%V

VCI: Inserts the two-digit VCI into the field. For example: "vci%V"will generate vci01 for clients on VCI 1 and vci02 for clients on VCI 2. Use only with atm ports.

%i

This is the most flexible of the commands, allowing an incrementing value to be specified. Three parameters control the operation of this option. <br/><br/> Start Value: The Start-width value is the first value to be used. Its width will be preserved when values are incremented. For example: `%001i' will generate 001, 002, 003, and so forth. <br/><br/> Count: The Count value specifies how many values will be generated before the first value is repeated. For example: `%001:3i' will generate 001, 002, 003, 001, 002, 003, 001, and so forth. That is, count values will be generated and then the start value will be repeated. <br/><br/> Repeat Count: The Repeat value specifies how many times each value will be repeated. For example: `%001::2i' will generate 001, 001, 002, 002, 003, 003, and so forth.

DEFAULT

circuit

distribution_alg_percentage

Supported platforms Details

IxNetwork

DESCRIPTION

Defines the percentage of deviation from a uniform distribution of DSL subscribers-to-access nodes. With the default value of 0%, the DSL subscribers are distributed among the access nodes according to the following algorithm: If the division of the number of subscribers by the number of access nodes produces a remainder of zero, the DSL subscribers are equally distributed among the access nodes. For example, if you have four access nodes and 80 subscribers, the default value of 0% results in an equal allocation of 20 subscribers to each access node.

If the division of the number of subscribers by the number of access nodes produces a non-zero remainder, the DSL subscribers are equally distributed among the access nodes, with the remaining number of nodes distributed equally, beginning with the first access node. For example, with eight subscribers and three access nodes, the distribution will be as follows: access node 1 will receive subscribers 0, 1, and 2; access node 2 will receive subscribers 3, 4, and 5; and access node 3 will receive subscribers 6 and 7.

If you set Distribution Algorithm Percentage to a value greater than zero, the distribution is accomplished according to the following algorithm: 1. First, IxNetwork calculates an even distribution of subscribers, using the method described above. 2. Next, IxNetwork groups the access nodes into pairs. If there is an odd number of access nodes, the last access node will keep its currently-allocated subscribers. 3. For each pair of access nodes, IxNetwork uses the percent of deviation to calculate the number of subscribers to move from the first access node to the second access node. For example, if you have four access nodes, 80 subscribers, and a Distribution Algorithm Percentage value of 50%, IxNetwork will move 50% of the subscribers from the first access node in each pair to the second access node. In this example, the first access node in each pair will have 10 subscribers, and the second access node will have 30 subscribers. The default is 0%, the minimum is 0%, and the maximum is 100%. Note: The accuracy of the DSL profile distribution increases as the number of emulated DSL subscribers grows. If you have between 50 and 100 subscribers, you may experience an deviation of 10 to 15 percent from the model. This parameter is supported using the following APIs: IxTclNetwork.

DEFAULT

0

circuit_id

Supported platforms Details

IxNetwork

DESCRIPTION

Defines one or more circuit IDs for the subscribers in the specific ANCP range. Circuit IDs enable the NAS to associate individual subscribers with distinct QoS requirements. Circuit ID is a string value, from 0 to 63 characters in length. The format strings can include normal alpha-numeric characters interspersed with instances of %-prefixed specifications. There are 5 %-prefixed specifications that can be used. This parameter is supported using the following APIs: IxTclNetwork.

Valid options are:

%L

Outer VLAN ID: Inserts the two-digit outer VLAN ID into the field. For example: "vlan%L" will generate vlan01 for clients on VLAN 1 and vlan02 for clients on VLAN 2. Use only with ethernet ports.

%I

Inner VLAN ID: Inserts the two-digit inner VLAN ID into the field. For example: "vlan%I" will generate vlan01 for clients on INNER VLAN 1 and vlan02 for clients on INNER VLAN 2. Use only with ethernet ports.

%v

VPI: Inserts the two-digit VPI into the field. For example: "vpi%v" will generate vpi01 for clients on VPI 1 and vpi02 for clients on VPI 2. Use only with atm ports.

%V

VCI: Inserts the two-digit VCI into the field. For example: "vci%V"will generate vci01 for clients on VCI 1 and vci02 for clients on VCI 2. Use only with atm ports.

%i

This is the most flexible of the commands, allowing an incrementing value to be specified. Three parameters control the operation of this option. <br/><br/> Start Value: The Start-width value is the first value to be used. Its width will be preserved when values are incremented. For example: `%001i' will generate 001, 002, 003, and so forth. <br/><br/> Count: The Count value specifies how many values will be generated before the first value is repeated. For example: `%001:3i' will generate 001, 002, 003, 001, 002, 003, 001, and so forth. That is, count values will be generated and then the start value will be repeated. <br/><br/> Repeat Count: The Repeat value specifies how many times each value will be repeated. For example: `%001::2i' will generate 001, 001, 002, 002, 003, 003, and so forth.

DEFAULT

circuit

1

distribution_alg_percentage

Supported platforms Details

IxNetwork

DESCRIPTION

Defines the percentage of deviation from a uniform distribution of DSL subscribers-to-access nodes. With the default value of 0%, the DSL subscribers are distributed among the access nodes according to the following algorithm: If the division of the number of subscribers by the number of access nodes produces a remainder of zero, the DSL subscribers are equally distributed among the access nodes. For example, if you have four access nodes and 80 subscribers, the default value of 0% results in an equal allocation of 20 subscribers to each access node.

If the division of the number of subscribers by the number of access nodes produces a non-zero remainder, the DSL subscribers are equally distributed among the access nodes, with the remaining number of nodes distributed equally, beginning with the first access node. For example, with eight subscribers and three access nodes, the distribution will be as follows: access node 1 will receive subscribers 0, 1, and 2; access node 2 will receive subscribers 3, 4, and 5; and access node 3 will receive subscribers 6 and 7.

If you set Distribution Algorithm Percentage to a value greater than zero, the distribution is accomplished according to the following algorithm: 1. First, IxNetwork calculates an even distribution of subscribers, using the method described above. 2. Next, IxNetwork groups the access nodes into pairs. If there is an odd number of access nodes, the last access node will keep its currently-allocated subscribers. 3. For each pair of access nodes, IxNetwork uses the percent of deviation to calculate the number of subscribers to move from the first access node to the second access node. For example, if you have four access nodes, 80 subscribers, and a Distribution Algorithm Percentage value of 50%, IxNetwork will move 50% of the subscribers from the first access node in each pair to the second access node. In this example, the first access node in each pair will have 10 subscribers, and the second access node will have 30 subscribers. The default is 0%, the minimum is 0%, and the maximum is 100%. Note: The accuracy of the DSL profile distribution increases as the number of emulated DSL subscribers grows. If you have between 50 and 100 subscribers, you may experience an deviation of 10 to 15 percent from the model. This parameter is supported using the following APIs: IxTclNetwork.

DEFAULT

0
